The direction vector of line \(q\) is \(\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}\). This is because the parametric equations for line \(q\) are \(x = 7 + 2s\) and \(y = 1 + 5s\), meaning that as \(s\) changes, the point \((x, y)\) moves in the direction of the vector \(\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}\).

We need to find a vector \(\begin{pmatrix} w_1 \\ w_2 \end{pmatrix}\) that is parallel to \(\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}\) and satisfies \(w_1 - w_2 = 3\). Clearly, \(\begin{pmatrix} w_1 \\ w_2 \end{pmatrix} = k \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}\) for some scalar \(k\). So, we can express \(w_1\) and \(w_2\) as \(w_1 = 2k\) and \(w_2 = 5k\). Substituting these into the equation \(w_1 - w_2 = 3\), we get:
