I0320 16:09:56.782053 127102378575424 reward_manager.py:164] prompts:	Let f(x) be defined as follows:
\[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
\frac{x}{2} & \text{ if }x\text{ is even}, \\
2x & \text{ if }x\text{ is odd}.
\end{array}
\right.\]
Consider the sequence $x_n$ defined by $x_0 = 7$ and $x_n = f(x_{n-1})$ for $n \geq 1$. Find the smallest value of $n$ such that $x_n = x_0$.
I0320 16:09:56.782144 127102378575424 reward_manager.py:164] completions:	 To determine the smallest value of \( n \) such that \( x_n = x_0 \) for the sequence defined by \( x_0 = 7 \) and \( x_n = f(x_{n-1}) \), we start by evaluating the function \( f \) at successive terms of the sequence.

Given:
\[ f(x) = \begin{cases}
\frac{x}{2} & \text{if } x \text{ is even}, \\
2x & \text{if } x \text{ is odd}.
\end{cases} \]

First, we compute \( x_1 \):
\[ x_0 = 7 \text{ (odd)}, \]
\[ x_1 = f(7) = 2 \times 7 = 14. \]

Next, we compute \( x_2 \):
\[ x_1 = 14 \text{ (even)}, \]
\[ x_2 = f(14) = \frac{14}{2} = 7. \]

We observe that \( x_2 = 7 \), which is the same as \( x_0 \). Therefore, the sequence repeats every two steps, and we have:
\[ x_0 = 7, \]
\[ x_1 = 14, \]
\[ x_2 = 7, \]
\[ x_3 = 14, \]
\[ \vdots \]

The smallest value of \( n \) such that \( x_n = x_0 \) is \( n = 2 \).

Thus, the answer is:
\[ \boxed{2} \]
