I0320 18:10:58.045706 127102378575424 reward_manager.py:164] completions:	 Given that \(\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{u}} \mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}\), we want to compute \(\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{v}} (3 \mathbf{u})\).

The formula for projecting a vector \(\mathbf{w}\) onto \(\mathbf{z}\) is:
\[
\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{z}} \mathbf{w} = \left( \frac{\mathbf{z} \cdot \mathbf{w}}{\mathbf{z} \cdot \mathbf{z}} \right) \mathbf{z}
\]
This means that \(\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{v}} (3 \mathbf{u})\) is equal to multiplying the projection of \(\mathbf{u}\) onto \(\mathbf{v}\) by 3. So, \(\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{v}} (3 \mathbf{u}) = 3 \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{v}} \mathbf{u}\).

Given that \(\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{u}} \mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}\), then \(\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{v}} \mathbf{u} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}\). Thus, \(\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{v}} (3 \mathbf{u}) = 3 \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ 3 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}\).

So, the answer is \(\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ 3 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}}\).
