Let's denote the number of permutations of the 5 bands on the 5 stages as P(B, S), where B represents the set of bands and S represents the set of stages.

We can simplify the problem by denoting P(B, S) as the number of ways to place the bands on the stages. To ensure that all possible band combinations are still valid and the maximum number of unique pairings is still being accounted for, the arrangement has to be such that any two bands can appear together on any stage.

The maximum number of unique band pairings is the sum of the permutations on the 5 stages divided by the factorial of the difference between the permutations. This quantity is also known as a permutation coefficient. Hence, the problem reduces to finding the permutation coefficient, "P(B, S), S = 5".

Since there are 5 bands playing exactly once on each of the 5 stages, the maximum number of valid band pairs is given by the permutation coefficient: $P(B, S) = \frac{ B!}{(B - S)!, so we can write:

$$P(B, S) = P(B, S) = \frac{B!}{(B - S)!, so P(B, 2) = \frac{B(B - 1))/2 and P(B, 1) = B. This is equivalent to finding the number of ways to place B objects into S bins, so we need to consider all possible permutations of the bands across the stages.

Therefore, the maximum number of unique band pairs is the number of permutations of the bands on the 5 stages: $P(B, S)$. Here, we can calculate this as the factorial of B divided by the factorial of the difference between B and S.

```python
